00:00:20.830 --> 00:00:22.550
PROFESSOR: So welcome back.

00:00:22.550 --> 00:00:27.170
And today, we will
solve one type

00:00:27.170 --> 00:00:33.890
of problem, a very
important problem,

00:00:33.890 --> 00:00:35.770
basically, the following.

00:00:35.770 --> 00:00:44.060
Suppose all that you have is a
single charge, but it can move.

00:00:44.060 --> 00:00:47.560
Here is the origin
of coordinates.

00:00:47.560 --> 00:00:50.700
This is the charge,
Q. Its position is

00:00:50.700 --> 00:00:54.570
given by some vector, z of t.

00:00:54.570 --> 00:00:56.140
And the charge can move.

00:00:56.140 --> 00:00:58.140
It can have a velocity.

00:00:58.140 --> 00:01:00.210
It can have an
acceleration, et cetera.

00:01:00.210 --> 00:01:04.250
And the problem is,
somewhere in space,

00:01:04.250 --> 00:01:08.680
at a point, p, what
is the electric field?

00:01:08.680 --> 00:01:13.740
What is the magnetic
field at all times?

00:01:13.740 --> 00:01:15.070
That's the problem.

00:01:15.070 --> 00:01:19.600
Now the differences between
different particular problems

00:01:19.600 --> 00:01:25.070
will be where we are and what
the charge is moving et cetera.

00:01:25.070 --> 00:01:29.850
In particular, we
will consider problems

00:01:29.850 --> 00:01:35.110
where this charge is oscillating
in a simple harmonic motion.

00:01:35.110 --> 00:01:36.860
It's along a line.

00:01:36.860 --> 00:01:38.480
And then, in another
problem, we'll

00:01:38.480 --> 00:01:41.530
consider it's rotating
with uniform velocity.

00:01:41.530 --> 00:01:46.090
But in principle, we
could be doing anything.

00:01:46.090 --> 00:01:50.230
So how do you calculate
the electric field?

00:01:50.230 --> 00:01:54.340
How do you find out what the
magnetic field is everywhere?

00:01:54.340 --> 00:01:57.600
Also, if there is an
electric and magnetic field,

00:01:57.600 --> 00:02:02.040
there will be flow of energy and
energy flux or pointing vector.

00:02:02.040 --> 00:02:04.930
What will that be
at that location?

00:02:04.930 --> 00:02:09.810
And finally, if a charge does
accelerate here and it does

00:02:09.810 --> 00:02:15.240
radiate energy, and
the question is,

00:02:15.240 --> 00:02:20.810
what is the average total power
radiated by such a charge?

00:02:20.810 --> 00:02:25.920
Now this kind of problem
is extremely important.

00:02:25.920 --> 00:02:28.680
It's important
just from the point

00:02:28.680 --> 00:02:31.960
of view of understanding
how the world works.

00:02:31.960 --> 00:02:34.020
There are charges
all over the place.

00:02:34.020 --> 00:02:35.730
And they are moving.

00:02:35.730 --> 00:02:37.920
And they do produce
electric magnetic fields.

00:02:43.170 --> 00:02:46.410
A problem like this
gives you insight

00:02:46.410 --> 00:02:49.590
how the phenomena takes place.

00:02:49.590 --> 00:02:53.320
But let me tell you
immediately, in general,

00:02:53.320 --> 00:02:57.442
this is a horrendous problem.

00:02:57.442 --> 00:03:01.950
You know that, if you
have charges in space,

00:03:01.950 --> 00:03:07.580
and you have electric
and magnetic fields,

00:03:07.580 --> 00:03:11.140
the charges, the currents, the
electric and magnetic fields

00:03:11.140 --> 00:03:13.670
have to satisfy Maxwell's
equations, those

00:03:13.670 --> 00:03:15.360
four Maxwell's equations.

00:03:15.360 --> 00:03:18.600
So you can imagine
how complicated

00:03:18.600 --> 00:03:23.930
it must be to find electric and
magnetic fields, in general,

00:03:23.930 --> 00:03:26.950
for some arbitrary
motion like this.

00:03:26.950 --> 00:03:29.780
And the answer is, you would
never be asked to do that.

00:03:29.780 --> 00:03:34.970
And you would never have to do
that, in general, analytically.

00:03:34.970 --> 00:03:39.440
If you really had a problem
like this that you had to solve,

00:03:39.440 --> 00:03:42.776
in general, you would
do it on a computer.

00:03:42.776 --> 00:03:43.275
All right?

00:03:46.050 --> 00:03:49.590
But let me continue.

00:03:54.090 --> 00:04:00.350
But it turns out that,
under certain conditions,

00:04:00.350 --> 00:04:03.680
this problem is not so hard.

00:04:03.680 --> 00:04:09.210
And yet, it contains
all the physics

00:04:09.210 --> 00:04:12.600
and gives you all the
insights you need.

00:04:12.600 --> 00:04:16.980
And that is the
following situation.

00:04:16.980 --> 00:04:25.840
If you have the charge moving
in a confined region, which

00:04:25.840 --> 00:04:29.010
is much smaller,
whose dimensions

00:04:29.010 --> 00:04:34.930
are much smaller than the
distance at which you are

00:04:34.930 --> 00:04:38.640
interested to calculate the
electric magnetic fields,

00:04:38.640 --> 00:04:44.290
suddenly, this problem does
not become hard, or in fact,

00:04:44.290 --> 00:04:48.480
not hard at all,
relatively speaking.

00:04:48.480 --> 00:04:52.790
So in some sense-- and this
often happens in physics

00:04:52.790 --> 00:04:56.630
when you are given
the problem-- you

00:04:56.630 --> 00:05:02.000
have to have an understanding
of the situation

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:09.730
in order to understand what the
person is asking you to solve.

00:05:09.730 --> 00:05:15.040
So in a situation like
this, the buzz words,

00:05:15.040 --> 00:05:17.650
or what you would find
is, for example, say,

00:05:17.650 --> 00:05:18.860
there is a charge.

00:05:18.860 --> 00:05:20.180
It's accelerating.

00:05:20.180 --> 00:05:25.280
Calculate the electric field at
a distance far from the charge,

00:05:25.280 --> 00:05:28.040
or the far field,
as it's called,

00:05:28.040 --> 00:05:29.460
rather than the near field.

00:05:33.790 --> 00:05:37.090
And the reason for
it is the following,

00:05:37.090 --> 00:05:44.240
in this case, that
the hard part of this

00:05:44.240 --> 00:05:49.440
is calculating the field
relatively near the charge,

00:05:49.440 --> 00:05:52.180
because there, you
have a superposition

00:05:52.180 --> 00:05:57.580
of this static field, for
example, the Coulomb field.

00:05:57.580 --> 00:06:00.780
If a charge is moving,
it's like a little current.

00:06:00.780 --> 00:06:04.580
And so it produces
the magnetic fields

00:06:04.580 --> 00:06:08.150
through the Biot-Savart
Law, et cetera.

00:06:08.150 --> 00:06:14.940
But these fields drop off,
like 1/r, from the charge.

00:06:26.650 --> 00:06:32.690
And so, if you are
far away, then,

00:06:32.690 --> 00:06:35.690
in general, in most
situations where you're

00:06:35.690 --> 00:06:38.350
interested in understanding
what's going on,

00:06:38.350 --> 00:06:42.490
you can ignore those fields,
because the further you

00:06:42.490 --> 00:06:44.800
are away, the smaller they are.

00:06:44.800 --> 00:06:48.190
And they become negligible.

00:06:48.190 --> 00:06:51.440
There is another
contribution to the field,

00:06:51.440 --> 00:06:55.600
to the electromagnetic field,
a very important contribution.

00:06:55.600 --> 00:06:59.970
And that is-- and
in fact, you know

00:06:59.970 --> 00:07:05.880
that, in vacuum, without
any charges there,

00:07:05.880 --> 00:07:12.920
you can have electric and
magnetic fields present

00:07:12.920 --> 00:07:17.810
that come from propagating
electromagnetic waves.

00:07:17.810 --> 00:07:21.460
And it turns out that, if
you have a charge which

00:07:21.460 --> 00:07:26.490
is accelerating,
that does produce

00:07:26.490 --> 00:07:30.120
an electromagnetic wave.

00:07:30.120 --> 00:07:34.520
And that does not drop
off as 1 over r squared,

00:07:34.520 --> 00:07:38.430
but as 1/r, much more slowly.

00:07:38.430 --> 00:07:41.940
So if you are far
away, you are dominated

00:07:41.940 --> 00:07:46.450
by the propagating
electromagnetic wave.

00:07:49.710 --> 00:07:53.480
Now it's not that
this is trivial,

00:07:53.480 --> 00:07:59.490
but certainly, the propagating
electromagnetic wave

00:07:59.490 --> 00:08:03.540
is much easier to calculate
without the presence

00:08:03.540 --> 00:08:05.530
of these other fields.

00:08:09.920 --> 00:08:16.330
Now Professor Walter Lewin
has done that in his classes.

00:08:16.330 --> 00:08:21.810
He has shown how, if you
have somewhere a charge which

00:08:21.810 --> 00:08:28.780
is accelerating, how it
generates an electric field far

00:08:28.780 --> 00:08:32.380
away from that charge
and a magnetic field.

00:08:32.380 --> 00:08:34.630
I won't derive it
for you, but I'll

00:08:34.630 --> 00:08:40.669
summarize what you have learned.

00:08:40.669 --> 00:08:44.290
Now for a second, I'll
just want to point out

00:08:44.290 --> 00:08:48.660
why the problem of
electromagnetic waves

00:08:48.660 --> 00:08:52.420
is more difficult than,
say, that of a string.

00:08:52.420 --> 00:08:57.080
The analogous problem we
want to recount for a string

00:08:57.080 --> 00:08:57.840
is the following.

00:08:57.840 --> 00:09:01.970
Suppose you have a string,
you hold it at one end.

00:09:01.970 --> 00:09:02.610
Right?

00:09:02.610 --> 00:09:08.200
And suppose I move this
one end sinusoidally?

00:09:08.200 --> 00:09:14.780
You know that a string
like this is a line.

00:09:14.780 --> 00:09:18.750
And in there are
oscillators, infinitely

00:09:18.750 --> 00:09:21.420
close to each other,
infinite number of them.

00:09:21.420 --> 00:09:23.700
All right?

00:09:23.700 --> 00:09:29.290
Each one moves along a single
line, say, up and down.

00:09:29.290 --> 00:09:33.290
So for each one,
it's a single number

00:09:33.290 --> 00:09:35.600
tells you what the
displacement is.

00:09:38.540 --> 00:09:43.600
You know that the string
satisfies the wave equation.

00:09:43.600 --> 00:09:48.460
If you put a
boundary at one end,

00:09:48.460 --> 00:09:54.140
the oscillator, the first one,
is somehow externally driven.

00:09:54.140 --> 00:09:56.470
That excites the
next one, et cetera.

00:09:56.470 --> 00:09:59.580
And you know that
the wave propagates.

00:09:59.580 --> 00:10:04.280
Now in the case of
electromagnetism

00:10:04.280 --> 00:10:08.890
of this kind of a problem,
the situation is very similar,

00:10:08.890 --> 00:10:11.550
but you have this
extra complication.

00:10:11.550 --> 00:10:16.880
In the string, each oscillator
was on the straight line

00:10:16.880 --> 00:10:22.050
and only moved up and
down in one direction.

00:10:22.050 --> 00:10:28.170
For a charge, every point
in space you could imagine,

00:10:28.170 --> 00:10:30.530
there is an oscillator.

00:10:30.530 --> 00:10:33.060
The excitation of
that oscillator

00:10:33.060 --> 00:10:36.660
is the electric and
the magnetic field.

00:10:36.660 --> 00:10:39.020
That's the analogous
to the displacement.

00:10:39.020 --> 00:10:41.310
But notice, already,
two quantities,

00:10:41.310 --> 00:10:43.830
electric and magnetic.

00:10:43.830 --> 00:10:47.220
Here, for the string,
you had the displacement,

00:10:47.220 --> 00:10:49.870
a single number
in one direction.

00:10:49.870 --> 00:10:52.860
Here, the electric and
the magnetic fields

00:10:52.860 --> 00:10:55.340
are vector quantities.

00:10:55.340 --> 00:10:59.040
So not only do you have them
spread in three dimensions,

00:10:59.040 --> 00:11:05.760
instead of along the
string, the displacement

00:11:05.760 --> 00:11:06.780
is a vector quantity.

00:11:06.780 --> 00:11:10.250
So is the directions in
three-dimensional space,

00:11:10.250 --> 00:11:11.010
et cetera.

00:11:11.010 --> 00:11:13.030
So that, in principle,
is the same,

00:11:13.030 --> 00:11:15.940
but it is much more complicated.

00:11:15.940 --> 00:11:18.940
But coming back
now, fortunately,

00:11:18.940 --> 00:11:26.230
if you analyze what happens,
if you take a charge,

00:11:26.230 --> 00:11:28.760
if it's stationary,
it does not radiate.

00:11:28.760 --> 00:11:32.150
It has the Coulomb field,
which, as I told you,

00:11:32.150 --> 00:11:35.160
drops off like 1 over r squared.

00:11:35.160 --> 00:11:37.330
If it's moving with
uniform velocity,

00:11:37.330 --> 00:11:42.720
for example, it does
generate magnetic fields.

00:11:42.720 --> 00:11:44.570
But again, they drop off.

00:11:44.570 --> 00:11:46.350
It doesn't radiate.

00:11:46.350 --> 00:11:53.310
But if it accelerates, then
it does produce, far away,

00:11:53.310 --> 00:12:00.330
an electron, a field
which propagates.

00:12:00.330 --> 00:12:04.830
And as Professor Walter Lewin
has showed in his lectures,

00:12:04.830 --> 00:12:07.500
you find the following.

00:12:07.500 --> 00:12:14.780
That if I have a charge
which accelerates,

00:12:14.780 --> 00:12:18.690
at the time when
it's accelerating,

00:12:18.690 --> 00:12:22.360
it produces an
electric field, which

00:12:22.360 --> 00:12:26.519
I can summarize
with this formula.

00:12:26.519 --> 00:12:27.435
So it's the following.

00:12:30.740 --> 00:12:37.350
Suppose, at the origin,
somewhere I have a charge.

00:12:37.350 --> 00:12:42.710
And it accelerates, say,
in some direction, up.

00:12:42.710 --> 00:12:48.610
And I am interested what
is the electric field that

00:12:48.610 --> 00:12:54.570
propagates outwards
in some direction, r.

00:12:54.570 --> 00:13:04.600
What one can show
is that this charge

00:13:04.600 --> 00:13:08.175
will propagate in all
directions, including

00:13:08.175 --> 00:13:08.800
this direction.

00:13:12.350 --> 00:13:18.970
But there's only one
component of the acceleration

00:13:18.970 --> 00:13:23.860
of the charge which gives
rise to the production

00:13:23.860 --> 00:13:27.280
of the field which propagates.

00:13:27.280 --> 00:13:30.370
And that is the
component which is

00:13:30.370 --> 00:13:34.230
perpendicular to the
direction in which I'm

00:13:34.230 --> 00:13:38.470
interested to calculate
the electric field.

00:13:38.470 --> 00:13:43.140
So if the charge, for example,
is accelerating upwards,

00:13:43.140 --> 00:13:46.900
like this, then it's
only the component

00:13:46.900 --> 00:13:52.950
of this acceleration which is
perpendicular to this line that

00:13:52.950 --> 00:13:56.580
gives rise to the
electric field.

00:13:56.580 --> 00:13:58.660
And one can calculate it.

00:13:58.660 --> 00:14:02.230
And its formula is
rather straightforward.

00:14:02.230 --> 00:14:07.540
You find the electric
field at some distance, r,

00:14:07.540 --> 00:14:08.605
from the charge.

00:14:11.150 --> 00:14:18.600
At time t, is
related to, as I say,

00:14:18.600 --> 00:14:24.940
this acceleration of the charge,
but only the component, which

00:14:24.940 --> 00:14:29.750
I call aperp, the component
of a perpendicular

00:14:29.750 --> 00:14:35.500
to this line, that's
this quantity.

00:14:35.500 --> 00:14:45.070
And what is interesting is the
field here that is produced

00:14:45.070 --> 00:14:53.290
is proportional to this
perpendicular component

00:14:53.290 --> 00:14:55.130
of the acceleration.

00:14:55.130 --> 00:15:01.030
But there is a difference
in time because,

00:15:01.030 --> 00:15:05.630
as this charge
accelerates-- it's

00:15:05.630 --> 00:15:08.140
analogous to take the string.

00:15:08.140 --> 00:15:10.330
When I took the
end of the string

00:15:10.330 --> 00:15:14.780
and I moved it, at
that instant, the kink

00:15:14.780 --> 00:15:19.100
got produced which
propagated along this string.

00:15:19.100 --> 00:15:20.510
Same happens here.

00:15:20.510 --> 00:15:23.900
If I have a charge
which accelerates,

00:15:23.900 --> 00:15:28.760
it produces an electric
field which propagates.

00:15:28.760 --> 00:15:32.390
And it propagates with
the velocity of light, c.

00:15:32.390 --> 00:15:40.010
So the field over here is
given by the acceleration

00:15:40.010 --> 00:15:44.950
of the charge at a time,
t prime, which is earlier.

00:15:44.950 --> 00:15:49.290
If you're interested in
the field here at time t,

00:15:49.290 --> 00:15:55.060
then you have to know what was
the acceleration of the charge

00:15:55.060 --> 00:15:58.160
here at the earlier
time, t prime,

00:15:58.160 --> 00:16:02.670
which is equal to
t minus r/c, which

00:16:02.670 --> 00:16:08.350
is the time the electric field
took to get to that point.

00:16:08.350 --> 00:16:09.430
That's the tricky part.

00:16:09.430 --> 00:16:14.780
This is the only tricky
part of this equation.

00:16:14.780 --> 00:16:20.290
So the electric field at
the position r at time t

00:16:20.290 --> 00:16:23.560
is related to the
acceleration of the charge,

00:16:23.560 --> 00:16:25.950
the perpendicular
component of it,

00:16:25.950 --> 00:16:30.280
at an earlier time times
some constants, the charge

00:16:30.280 --> 00:16:31.610
and a constant.

00:16:31.610 --> 00:16:35.331
And it drops off like 1/r.

00:16:35.331 --> 00:16:35.830
OK?

00:16:52.020 --> 00:16:55.320
So this is the crucial equation.

00:16:55.320 --> 00:17:00.370
It tells us that, as I
say-- I'm repeating this,

00:17:00.370 --> 00:17:02.960
because it's so important.

00:17:02.960 --> 00:17:06.230
Whenever I have a charge
which is accelerating,

00:17:06.230 --> 00:17:11.079
it, at that instant,
produces an electric field

00:17:11.079 --> 00:17:16.050
which is moving outwards
at the speed of light.

00:17:16.050 --> 00:17:21.730
Its amplitude is dropping
like 1/r, all right?

00:17:21.730 --> 00:17:23.740
And goes on forever.

00:17:23.740 --> 00:17:26.400
Now you know from
Maxwell's equations,

00:17:26.400 --> 00:17:31.890
if you have an electric field
which is propagating like that,

00:17:31.890 --> 00:17:35.660
associated, there will
be a magnetic field.

00:17:35.660 --> 00:17:39.940
This is now just the
same as you've always

00:17:39.940 --> 00:17:42.960
seen for electromagnetic waves.

00:17:42.960 --> 00:17:44.990
I like sort of visualizing.

00:17:44.990 --> 00:17:47.880
If an electromagnetic wave
moves in that direction,

00:17:47.880 --> 00:17:51.170
and the electric field is this
direction, at that instant,

00:17:51.170 --> 00:17:55.120
there will be a magnetic
field perpendicular to it.

00:17:55.120 --> 00:17:58.380
And the B is proportional
to E. And they both

00:17:58.380 --> 00:18:00.040
move forward like that.

00:18:00.040 --> 00:18:00.790
OK?

00:18:00.790 --> 00:18:06.170
So if this is E, then
you can get from a B.

00:18:06.170 --> 00:18:07.670
They are proportional
to each other.

00:18:07.670 --> 00:18:10.800
There's just that constant,
C, because the units.

00:18:10.800 --> 00:18:13.720
And they are perpendicular
to each other.

00:18:13.720 --> 00:18:14.220
OK.

00:18:14.220 --> 00:18:17.660
So if you understand
this formula,

00:18:17.660 --> 00:18:21.480
all the problems that you
would be normally asked

00:18:21.480 --> 00:18:26.060
can extremely
easily be done, OK?

00:18:26.060 --> 00:18:28.040
Once you know E
and B, of course,

00:18:28.040 --> 00:18:30.350
you can calculate
at every location.

00:18:30.350 --> 00:18:34.080
The Poynting vector is just a
cross product between those.

00:18:34.080 --> 00:18:39.260
And I just summarize them on
the formula we may need later.

00:18:39.260 --> 00:18:41.640
So I'm now going to
start from scratch

00:18:41.640 --> 00:18:44.090
by taking a concrete example.

00:18:44.090 --> 00:18:44.710
All right?

00:18:44.710 --> 00:18:49.750
So if this refresher didn't
help, maybe the problem

00:18:49.750 --> 00:18:51.500
itself will.

00:18:51.500 --> 00:18:53.955
So now let's take
a concrete example.

00:18:57.180 --> 00:19:02.840
I'll take a single
