00:38:30.980 --> 00:38:35.570
If it radiates energy,
of course, normally,

00:38:35.570 --> 00:38:40.950
it would have to finally stop.

00:38:40.950 --> 00:38:45.730
But I'm assuming there is
some mechanism which uniformly

00:38:45.730 --> 00:38:52.420
maintains the motion of these
charges in a certain motion.

00:38:52.420 --> 00:38:54.710
Energy will be radiated.

00:38:54.710 --> 00:39:01.410
And I want to calculate what
is the total energy radiated

00:39:01.410 --> 00:39:04.990
per second by this charge.

00:39:04.990 --> 00:39:09.957
And the way we are going to
do this-- so the question now

00:39:09.957 --> 00:39:16.040
is, for this particular charge,
oscillating like we discussed,

00:39:16.040 --> 00:39:20.120
what is the total energy
per second-- in other words,

00:39:20.120 --> 00:39:24.100
power-- radiated at
the time t prime?

00:39:27.660 --> 00:39:32.280
Clearly, if it's
radiating energy outwards,

00:39:32.280 --> 00:39:34.910
by conservation of
energy, the amount

00:39:34.910 --> 00:39:38.250
of energy coming
out of this will

00:39:38.250 --> 00:39:43.090
be the same as the
amount of energy crossing

00:39:43.090 --> 00:39:50.930
a sphere of radius,
R, at a later time.

00:39:50.930 --> 00:39:56.580
So if I calculate the energy
crossing a sphere at the time

00:39:56.580 --> 00:40:01.220
t, where t is this
t prime plus R/C,

00:40:01.220 --> 00:40:06.240
at a later time, that
will be the total energy

00:40:06.240 --> 00:40:11.440
per second radiated by this
charge at the time, t prime.

00:40:11.440 --> 00:40:15.900
So I will now
calculate the energy

00:40:15.900 --> 00:40:22.500
per second which is crossing
the surface of this sphere

00:40:22.500 --> 00:40:25.720
at the time, t.

00:40:25.720 --> 00:40:28.450
Well, how much energy
is crossing the surface?

00:40:28.450 --> 00:40:34.340
We know that, at the
surface of this sphere,

00:40:34.340 --> 00:40:41.240
there is, at every location,
an electric field which

00:40:41.240 --> 00:40:44.140
is parallel to the
surface, because this

00:40:44.140 --> 00:40:47.280
is perpendicular to R.
The electric field is

00:40:47.280 --> 00:40:49.080
perpendicular to this.

00:40:49.080 --> 00:40:53.310
So at this location, for
example, the electric field

00:40:53.310 --> 00:40:57.530
will be like this,
crossing it, part

00:40:57.530 --> 00:41:00.080
of the surface of this sphere.

00:41:00.080 --> 00:41:04.000
There will be a magnetic
field perpendicular to it.

00:41:04.000 --> 00:41:07.470
And so, at this
location, there will

00:41:07.470 --> 00:41:11.720
be a energy flux, the
so-called Poynting vector,

00:41:11.720 --> 00:41:16.800
the energy per second
crossing a unit [INAUDIBLE].

00:41:16.800 --> 00:41:20.050
And that's this vector,
s, the Poynting vector,

00:41:20.050 --> 00:41:23.030
which, as you know
from Professor Walter

00:41:23.030 --> 00:41:27.740
Lewin's lectures, is E cross
B. I forgot my vector sign

00:41:27.740 --> 00:41:35.550
on top of the B. These are
vectors, of course, E cross B.

00:41:35.550 --> 00:41:40.700
Now we know, for an
electromagnetic wave in vacuum,

00:41:40.700 --> 00:41:45.280
that the E and B are
perpendicular and proportional

00:41:45.280 --> 00:41:48.060
to each other, just the
fact the C. So this will

00:41:48.060 --> 00:41:54.430
be the magnitude of E squared
divided by this mu 0 times

00:41:54.430 --> 00:41:57.400
C, because B is E/C.

00:41:57.400 --> 00:41:59.310
This is a scalar quant--
these were vectors.

00:41:59.310 --> 00:42:00.970
This is a scalar.

00:42:00.970 --> 00:42:09.000
So this is the energy flowing
per unit area, per unit time

00:42:09.000 --> 00:42:10.455
at the surface of this.

00:42:13.330 --> 00:42:20.000
And the E will depend on
the location on this sphere.

00:42:20.000 --> 00:42:24.060
So what is the
total energy that's

00:42:24.060 --> 00:42:28.700
leaving the charge
at time t prime?

00:42:28.700 --> 00:42:34.330
It will be the sum
of all the energies

00:42:34.330 --> 00:42:36.410
that are coming
out per unit area

00:42:36.410 --> 00:42:39.940
along this surface at time t.

00:42:39.940 --> 00:42:46.140
So it's going to be
the integral of SdA.

00:42:46.140 --> 00:42:50.410
What I'm doing, basically,
calculating at every location

00:42:50.410 --> 00:42:54.870
S multiplied by the area
there-- so that gives me

00:42:54.870 --> 00:42:57.010
how much energy goes
through that area--

00:42:57.010 --> 00:43:00.470
and adding them
across the surface

00:43:00.470 --> 00:43:03.600
everywhere around
the complete sphere.

00:43:03.600 --> 00:43:07.350
That will be the total
energy leaving here.

00:43:07.350 --> 00:43:10.170
So imagine this is
oscillating up and down,

00:43:10.170 --> 00:43:14.460
radiating these
spherical waves outwards.

00:43:14.460 --> 00:43:16.670
And they cross this surface.

00:43:16.670 --> 00:43:21.190
And at every place, there is
energy flowing, the Poynting

00:43:21.190 --> 00:43:21.790
vector.

00:43:21.790 --> 00:43:23.850
And here, I'm adding them all.

00:43:23.850 --> 00:43:28.790
This will be the
total power radiated

00:43:28.790 --> 00:43:32.521
by this charge at that
earlier time, t prime.

00:43:32.521 --> 00:43:33.020
OK.

00:43:33.020 --> 00:43:37.660
So I now have to just log
through and calculate this.

00:43:37.660 --> 00:43:42.615
S, I have to
calculate from this.

00:43:45.460 --> 00:43:51.190
And then I have to
calculate the piece of area.

00:43:51.190 --> 00:43:55.120
Well, let me tell
you what I will do.

00:43:55.120 --> 00:44:01.480
From what we've learned
from the earlier part,

00:44:01.480 --> 00:44:11.150
the magnitude of E only
depended on this angle, theta,

00:44:11.150 --> 00:44:13.220
and this distance.

00:44:13.220 --> 00:44:18.080
So imagine, along the
surface, I take a slice

00:44:18.080 --> 00:44:26.470
this surface, like this, where
every point along this surface

00:44:26.470 --> 00:44:32.890
is at an angle, theta,
to the z-axis, OK?

00:44:36.400 --> 00:44:39.040
And it's a thin slice.

00:44:39.040 --> 00:44:41.890
So what will be this distance?

00:44:41.890 --> 00:44:44.830
I'll take this to be d theta.

00:44:44.830 --> 00:44:49.450
This distance is R, so that
distance is already Rd theta.

00:44:49.450 --> 00:44:55.050
If I multiply that
by 2 pi r sine theta,

00:44:55.050 --> 00:45:02.020
r sine theta is the
radius of this circle.

00:45:02.020 --> 00:45:07.850
So this total area going all
the way around this sphere

00:45:07.850 --> 00:45:14.790
is 2 pi r sine theta
multiplied by Rd theta.

00:45:14.790 --> 00:45:16.050
OK?

00:45:16.050 --> 00:45:22.720
So now along this,
everywhere, S is the same.

00:45:22.720 --> 00:45:25.970
So if S is at that
angle, theta, and I've

00:45:25.970 --> 00:45:31.250
multiplied by 2 pi R
sine theta Rd theta,

00:45:31.250 --> 00:45:36.120
this is the piece of area,
if I multiply by that,

00:45:36.120 --> 00:45:43.370
this gives me the total
energy flux or power

00:45:43.370 --> 00:45:52.490
that is leaving the sphere
along this part, all

00:45:52.490 --> 00:45:57.070
the way behind there,
all the way around.

00:45:57.070 --> 00:45:59.960
OK?

00:45:59.960 --> 00:46:03.920
Now what is the total
energy per second leaving

00:46:03.920 --> 00:46:06.950
this complete sphere
is the addition

00:46:06.950 --> 00:46:11.010
of pieces like that for
the complete sphere.

00:46:11.010 --> 00:46:15.730
So it would be the
integral of this

00:46:15.730 --> 00:46:18.390
for theta going from 0 to pi.

00:46:21.070 --> 00:46:23.410
And then I've covered
the compete sphere.

00:46:23.410 --> 00:46:26.770
So that will be
this integral, which

00:46:26.770 --> 00:46:29.870
is the power radiated
by the charge.

00:46:29.870 --> 00:46:32.540
OK, if you've understood
that, then it's

00:46:32.540 --> 00:46:36.550
just pure algebra now.

00:46:36.550 --> 00:46:39.470
S, I can calculate,
because I know

00:46:39.470 --> 00:46:44.180
it's the magnitude of
E squared over C mu 0.

00:46:44.180 --> 00:46:47.550
But that, we've already done.

00:46:47.550 --> 00:46:49.070
We did it for 30 degrees.

00:46:49.070 --> 00:46:50.310
And now do it for theta.

00:46:50.310 --> 00:46:54.430
So here, instead of having
sine 30, which was 1/2,

00:46:54.430 --> 00:46:57.870
I have sine theta there.

00:46:57.870 --> 00:47:03.215
So that squared gives me
this divided by C mu 0 that.

00:47:09.200 --> 00:47:15.120
And of course, it depends--
so this is what E is.

00:47:15.120 --> 00:47:22.880
But it's oscillating as
cosine omega times this.

00:47:22.880 --> 00:47:26.080
And we have to square it,
because this is E squared.

00:47:26.080 --> 00:47:33.760
So this is what the
Poynting vector is at,

00:47:33.760 --> 00:47:39.370
the angle theta, distance
R away at time t, OK?

00:47:39.370 --> 00:47:41.830
And therefore,
the total power is

00:47:41.830 --> 00:47:48.060
this multiplied by that
integrated from 0 to pi.

00:47:48.060 --> 00:47:51.980
I've just rewritten
it, this quantity,

00:47:51.980 --> 00:47:53.450
plugging that into here.

00:47:53.450 --> 00:47:55.470
I end up with this.

00:47:55.470 --> 00:47:58.090
Everything does not
depend on theta,

00:47:58.090 --> 00:48:03.320
except sine theta, which
you have a squared from here

00:48:03.320 --> 00:48:04.950
and another sign from there.

00:48:04.950 --> 00:48:07.980
So I get sine cubed
theta d theta.

00:48:07.980 --> 00:48:10.150
OK, we're home.

00:48:10.150 --> 00:48:12.600
So that's the answer.

00:48:12.600 --> 00:48:17.400
Because this you can do,
I won't waste your time.

00:48:17.400 --> 00:48:21.310
The way to do it is you can
take sine theta d theta to be

00:48:21.310 --> 00:48:25.170
d cosine theta, and
then integrating sine

00:48:25.170 --> 00:48:28.080
squared theta d cosine theta.

00:48:28.080 --> 00:48:31.600
And if you do that, you get 4/3.

00:48:31.600 --> 00:48:34.250
So I plug 4/3 in
for that integral.

00:48:34.250 --> 00:48:38.790
This is the answer, OK?

00:48:38.790 --> 00:48:46.810
So what we see
now, through any--

00:48:46.810 --> 00:48:51.390
and it's independent of R, which
I hope did not surprise you.

00:48:51.390 --> 00:48:53.880
It's a statement of
conservation of energy,

00:48:53.880 --> 00:48:56.520
because you have this
charge oscillating

00:48:56.520 --> 00:48:59.000
up and down, radiating.

00:48:59.000 --> 00:49:04.370
Through every sphere of radius
R, the same amount of energy

00:49:04.370 --> 00:49:06.345
has to go through,
or otherwise, you'

00:49:06.345 --> 00:49:08.350
d be gaining or losing energy.

00:49:08.350 --> 00:49:10.057
So that's a check.

00:49:10.057 --> 00:49:10.640
You can check.

00:49:10.640 --> 00:49:14.130
If R came into this formula,
