00:49:14.130 --> 00:49:16.360
And the only place
where it does,

00:49:16.360 --> 00:49:21.010
is only-- it oscillates,
so at any position, R,

00:49:21.010 --> 00:49:23.890
the energy going through
oscillates, because it's

00:49:23.890 --> 00:49:25.840
a wave going out, OK?

00:49:25.840 --> 00:49:29.550
So this changes the phase,
but not the magnitude.

00:49:29.550 --> 00:49:33.600
In the actual question,
it asked for what

00:49:33.600 --> 00:49:38.920
is the time average
that's radiated outwards.

00:49:38.920 --> 00:49:42.760
So we want to know the
time average of this.

00:49:42.760 --> 00:49:49.375
And that's the time
average of that is here.

00:49:52.070 --> 00:49:58.980
You know that the time average
of cosine some function of t

00:49:58.980 --> 00:49:59.980
is 1/2.

00:49:59.980 --> 00:50:04.670
If you take cosine--
sorry, cosine squared,

00:50:04.670 --> 00:50:05.940
which was in here, cosine.

00:50:05.940 --> 00:50:09.200
So the time average of
cosine squared is 1/2.

00:50:09.200 --> 00:50:12.790
So finally, we get that
the average, time average,

00:50:12.790 --> 00:50:17.070
power leaving this
oscillating charge

00:50:17.070 --> 00:50:18.434
is given by this formula.

00:50:18.434 --> 00:50:19.725
It's actually a famous formula.

00:50:19.725 --> 00:50:24.310
It's called
[? Lambor ?] formula.

00:50:24.310 --> 00:50:25.340
OK?

00:50:25.340 --> 00:50:28.260
So that's the total
energy radiated.

00:50:28.260 --> 00:50:29.670
Fine.

