So this will radiate in that
direction circularly polarized

00:56:38.630 --> 00:56:39.840
light.

00:56:39.840 --> 00:56:42.610
If I look from
above, what do I see?

00:56:42.610 --> 00:56:45.410
The charge is going
like this, so I just

00:56:45.410 --> 00:56:48.250
see this component
from above-- you

00:56:48.250 --> 00:56:51.470
can look at the two
components-- like that.

00:56:51.470 --> 00:56:55.470
So straight up, I'll see
linearly polarized light.

00:56:55.470 --> 00:56:59.460
If I look from the side, I
see it's going up and down.

00:56:59.460 --> 00:57:04.090
I will see also
linearly polarized,

00:57:04.090 --> 00:57:06.310
but in a different direction.

00:57:06.310 --> 00:57:10.050
So a charge like
this, as before,

00:57:10.050 --> 00:57:12.400
will radiate in all directions.

00:57:12.400 --> 00:57:16.640
But the extra complication now
is, in different directions,

00:57:16.640 --> 00:57:18.830
it'll be different polarization.

00:57:18.830 --> 00:57:20.990
For example, if I'm
looking at this from here,

00:57:20.990 --> 00:57:24.180
this crazy angle,
what I will see

00:57:24.180 --> 00:57:28.380
is I will see a component from
the acceleration like this,

00:57:28.380 --> 00:57:31.930
and from that, but they
have different amplitude.

00:57:31.930 --> 00:57:36.179
And so I'll get the
two polarizations which

00:57:36.179 --> 00:57:37.720
are different
amplitudes, corresponds

00:57:37.720 --> 00:57:39.770
to elliptically polarized light.

00:57:39.770 --> 00:57:43.100
So in this direction, I'll
see an elliptically polarized

00:57:43.100 --> 00:57:44.700
light.

00:57:44.700 --> 00:57:48.680
And using this formula
any place in space,

00:57:48.680 --> 00:57:52.430
you can calculate the
electric and magnetic field,

00:57:52.430 --> 00:57:56.320
just doing the same as
we did before, but take

00:57:56.320 --> 00:58:02.530
the full vector description
of the perpendicular

00:58:02.530 --> 00:58:05.820
component of the
acceleration of the charge.

00:58:05.820 --> 00:58:09.010
So let me stop there and
just sort of summarize.

00:58:09.010 --> 00:58:12.230
In principle, we've
done just very little.

00:58:12.230 --> 00:58:16.680
What we showed today
is, in general,

00:58:16.680 --> 00:58:21.480
if I have a charge which
moving with some velocity,

00:58:21.480 --> 00:58:23.440
some acceleration,
et cetera, it'll

00:58:23.440 --> 00:58:26.150
be surrounded by a
very complicated field.

00:58:26.150 --> 00:58:28.470
There will be the Coulomb
field, the Biot-Savart field,

00:58:28.470 --> 00:58:31.120
the radiated field, et cetera.

00:58:31.120 --> 00:58:34.139
If you need to solve the
complete thing properly,

00:58:34.139 --> 00:58:35.180
you will need a computer.

00:58:35.180 --> 00:58:36.730
You can't do it.

00:58:36.730 --> 00:58:42.540
But if you are only interested
in the radiated field which

00:58:42.540 --> 00:58:47.240
is far away from the
accelerated charge,

00:58:47.240 --> 00:58:50.570
it turns out the situation
is sufficiently simple,

00:58:50.570 --> 00:58:54.310
you can do it almost on
the back of an envelope.

00:58:54.310 --> 00:58:57.620
All you need to know, if you
are interested in the field

00:58:57.620 --> 00:59:01.460
in any location, is
you ask yourself,

00:59:01.460 --> 00:59:07.950
at an earlier time, what
was the charge doing?

00:59:07.950 --> 00:59:13.680
And by earlier, I mean
at time that light

00:59:13.680 --> 00:59:17.650
had time to come from
the charge to me.

00:59:17.650 --> 00:59:22.130
So I take that distance, R/C,
and at that earlier time,

00:59:22.130 --> 00:59:25.030
I need to know what
the charge was doing.

00:59:25.030 --> 00:59:28.870
I ask myself, in which
direction it was accelerating?

00:59:28.870 --> 00:59:31.590
I take the magnitude
of acceleration,

00:59:31.590 --> 00:59:35.740
which is perpendicular to the
direction in which I'm looking,

00:59:35.740 --> 00:59:40.710
and I calculate that and
multiply by some constants

00:59:40.710 --> 00:59:43.640
that we've done
over and over again,

00:59:43.640 --> 00:59:45.960
and that will tell me what
the electric field is.

00:59:45.960 --> 00:59:47.900
From that, I can get
the magnetic field,

00:59:47.900 --> 00:59:49.360
and I get the full radiation.

00:59:49.360 --> 00:59:51.210
Thank you.

